A crushing blow with the blunt end of a sword.

NPCs are secondary game agents that are not inherently hostile to characters. They can fill useful role such as bankers merchants or guards. Or accompany characters as companions. Like mooks, their levelling system is simplified. Unlike characters, NPCs don't have agency and cannot actively interact with the world, only be interacted with.
Seek instant contact with the enemy over a distance

A fixed station necessary to perform some actions, such as cooking or brewing. A character must be adjacent to an unused work station to get access to it.Some amenities, like a campfire, bestow benefits to adjacent characters.
Throw several projectiles at the same target in quick succession.

A catch-all term for the criminal element in the city. Gangs, mobsters and power-hungry craftmen battle each other for the control of the least secured areas, such a the docks. No single master rules the underworld, not for lack of trying by all concerned.

Fire two arrows at once at the target with a limited penalty to accuracy.
Spend as much time as needed in order to ensure a hit. As any attack will break the shooter's concentration and cancel the shot, it is best used from cover as an opening attack.
A heavy, slow, strike breaking the target's defence if it connects.
{blackCape}  capes are equipped in the cape slot. They typically offer protection against the weather or a discretion bonus.
A single-shot pistol chambered for a small calibre round used in firing competitions. Pricey, but very precise up to middle-range.
Regular pistol ammunition. Relatively weak due to the pressure constraints of pistols.
Knives, daggers, swords or cutlasses, blades rely on their sharp edge to injure the enemy. They are very effective against unarmoured targets, but less so against armoured enemies or constructs.

The old-fashioned, well established discipline of borrowing power from the ethereal entities. Hermetic mages do not have a shred of power themselves, only knowledge to coax it from rituals and channel it through crafted items using symbiology.An expensive calling because of the material's cost.numerologyastrologycabalism
An access point for the mundanes to access the city's communication boards and for craftmen to manage their finances through the financing network.

Attribute develop in a similar manner to skills, but differs in that they don't unlock new abilities. Each attribute is linked to an attribute multiplier, which determines its growth rate. Stats are entirely derived from attributes.
A perk point is earned at each new level in a primary attribute.

Melee fighting remains a viable combat choice in the modern age despite the advent of firearms because of techniques negating the former's efficiency and firearms sometimes poor reliability. Abilities define the actions taken by a agent or the reaction of the agent to its environment. Abilities are tied to skills, and progressing in a skill branch will unlock higher tier abilities.Abilities are divided between active abilities, which are actions requiring AP that must be initiated, and passive abilities which do not.

Any items that allow by itself or with others to perform a specific active action. Some interact with the environment, like a lighter. Others are necessary for crafting. Tools may or may not be depleted after use.
Very versatile and easy to acquire, knives are ubiquitous around the city, from street-gangs shives to mercooking knives

Best understood as an "hero role" in the story, titles represent a synergy of skills and attribute which, once attained, grant further bonuses. In game, titles are special permanent status effects Each title requires a minimum levels in one or several skills in order to be attained. A starting title often serve as a basis for newly generated characters. Setting a title to be achieved as a goal allows for automatic levelling. A character will hold all the titles he has accrued, but some will supersede former titles (their benefits are of a same nature and won't stack).//A reduction of those skills or attributes will cause a character to lose his archetype. A single character can have the requisite for several //archetypes; only one at a time can be active. Switching between archetypes is always possible but require time before the bonuses come into //effect.

An agent is an game entity capable of initiating actions in the world. It owns a pool of action points which regenerate with time. It is most often but not always capable of movement. Agents are divided between characters, mooks and summons.
A showy, and maybe ill advised, move to deflect arrows and other projectiles with a blade.
A pool of toxic liquid which impede movements.
For the purpose of the game, any item offering protection or stats boosts to the wearer is defined as equipment. Gameplay wise, those items are fitted into a character's equipment slot.
A primitive ancestor to the shotgun. A blunderbuss is a one-shot gunpowder weapon with very short range and poor accuracy. It can be loaded with nails or shots.
craft - shamblers lost all their soulstuff and turned to monsters
Bear the mark of the outsider
Strike the joints in the enemy armour to inflict damage with a blade weapon.
Consumables can be used by their owner in order to apply a temporary status effect, typically in order ro restore a pool resource.

Hats and helmets, everything than can be worn on one's head for fashion or for protection against attack and the environment. Occupy the Head slot. Some helmets preclude the use of masks or goggles.

Mooks are agents with set abilities and equipment that serves as opposition to the characters or simply if not hostile to fill the environment. They do not learn new abilities, but can upgrade to a higher tier version once they collect enough experience. A human mook can be upgraded to a new character in some cases. Mooks are more restricted than NPCs inasmuch as they can't interact with characters beyond fighting or ignoring them.

Professions represent the synergy between similar skills. They are related to a primary attribute, and each contribute toward its related attribute's growth as mediated by its attribute multiplier. Like skills, a profession level cannot surpass its related primary attribute's level and new profession levels give access to new abilities.
The characters are agents with the ability to learn new skills through experience. They are the main actors, the ones moving events in the world.
Draw and strike in a single lighting-fast movment.

The city is divided into a number maps, which are the environment in which agents dwell and map objects are placed. Maps are composed of blocks of different types, and are linked to each other by exit point with a fixed travel time. Some travel points are one-way.

Craft is the art of manipulating life-force or soulstuff to pursue own's ends. Unlike the teaching of old which sought power though the intercession of ethereal entities, craftsmen have learned, some say stolen, the techniques to manipulate the life force on their own, making them the equal of gods. This ability has revolutionised all aspect of life, and nearly all advanced technology in the city depends on craft at some level. //witches builder and spirit hackers cultivation: craft - compact soul for storage - refine soul, break soulstuff flow (disrupt magic and curses)        geas > imposed personality restriction  :  obey no-fighting believe

Assigning perks allows to flesh out a character in order to make him more unique. For each level gained in a attribute, perk points are earned for that can be spent to acquire perks. Some perks also require other perks to have been acquired before being available to purchase.
